{{Unreferenced|date=January 2010}}

'''Emily Blatch''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]], [[Royal Society of Arts|FRSA]] (24 July 1937 &ndash; 31 May 2005) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.

Born as '''Emily May Triggs''', the daughter of Stephen and Sarah Triggs, she was educated at [[Prenton]] and at Huntingdonshire College. At the age of 18, she joined the [[Women's Auxiliary Air Force]] and served as an [[air traffic control]] assistant between 1955 and 1959. 

From 1977 to 1989 Blatch was a councillor on [[Cambridgeshire]] [[County Council]] and was council leader. She was created '''Baroness Blatch''', of Hinchingbrooke in the County of [[Cambridgeshire]] on 4 July 1987. From 1991 to 1994, she was [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Education]]  and [[Home Office|Minister of State for the Home Office]] from 1994 to 1997. In 1997 she was given an honorary [[Doctor of Law|doctorate of Law]] from the [[University of Teesside]] and was [[Leader of the Opposition (UK)|Deputy Leader of the Opposition]] in 2001. 

==Family==
On 7 September 1963, she married John Richard Blatch (a [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] pilot) and they had four children: David (b. 1965 - d. 1979), James Richard (b. 1967) and twins, Andrew Edward (b. 1968) and Elizabeth Anne (b. 1968).

==Death==
Blatch died of [[pancreatic cancer]] in 2005, aged 67.

